<TITLE> ZTE says to buy up to $500 mln chips from Qualcomm </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 HONG KONG, June 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - ZTE Corp said on Monday it has raised to US$500 million from US$300 million the value of chips it will purchase from Qualcomm as part of an agreement covering 2006 to 2007. China's second-largest telecoms gear maker said it had also entered into contracts with China Mobile Communication Corp. for supply of products and services, valued at up to 2.37 billion yuan (US$308.7 million) for the construction of a trial network for its TD-SCDMA application. Product sales to China Mobile account for 90 percent of the contract total, ZTE added. In April, ZTE had said it had won an order to supply the parent of China Mobile with equipment for the country's first high-speed wireless network. China Mobile is tendering contracts -- worth 26.7 billion yuan ($3.5 billion), according to domestic media reports -- to build a network for China's homegrown 3G standard, TD-SCDMA (Time Division Synchronous Code Division Multiple Access). Shares of ZTE rose 3.1 percent to HK$39.70 in late morning trade on Monday. (US$1=HK$7.8=7.676 yua
